            "in_reply_to_account_id": "108431110488823039",
            "sensitive": false,
            "spoiler_text": "",
            "visibility": "public",
            "language": "en",
            "uri": "https://climatejustice.social/users/kentpitman/statuses/112949119567983703",
            "url": "https://climatejustice.social/@kentpitman/112949119567983703",
            "replies_count": 0,
            "reblogs_count": 1,
            "favourites_count": 1,
            "edited_at": null,
            "content": "<p><span class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"><a href=\"https://mastodon.social/@itsveganjim\" class=\"u-url mention\" rel=\"nofollow noopener noreferrer\" target=\"_blank\">@<span>itsveganjim</span></a></span> </p><p>I somewhat agree, though I would personally add: don't worry about being complete or  perfect.</p><p>ANY move in the vegan direction matters. Doing it completely can be complicated, so do what you can.</p><p>Not to mention many people are put off by vegan hardliners, so vegans need to be kind to people who are experimenting.</p><p>If just starting, take it at a pace you can do, because sourcing ingredients and learning new ways can be hard work, and nothing is gained by making it so painful for yourself that you snap back and decide it's too hard.</p><p>If the whole world went 50% vegan, a much more achievable near-term goal, it'd be better than if the 10% went vegan and, in the process, sufficiently ticked off others that those others drew battle lines.</p><p>Doing vegan Fridays, or something like that, opens doors to experimentation with more days. It's important to convince yourself it's possible.</p><p>Seek out and choose meatless options for burgers, like Beyond Burger or Impossible Burger, as another way to be incremental. It creates conversational opportunities with friends and restaurants. I do this without thinking now, and why not? It's tasty.</p><p>Some people have food issues (allergies, weight issues, missing organs, etc ) that can be complicated to mesh with veganism. Vegans need to cut these people some slack. Hard line nitpickiness sets the movement back.</p><p>Same with restaurants. I ate vegan for a while (and still try to minimize meat where I can), but I found restaurants who said they'd been willing to do things that were approximately vegan, but they just got chided for very legit efforts and swore off trying. Maybe a sauce had some small meat product or even they had meatless dishes but couldn't afford a separate stove to guarantee meat and nonmeat were cooked on different surfaces. Stop calling well-intentioned people frauds or failures or clueless, and instead create a whole spectrum of positive terminology so well-intentioned people can position themselves along it.</p>",
